video_description: Please respect cosplayers and peoples boundaries at anime conventions 🩵 #animeconvention #animecon #storytime #comiccon #cosplayer #cosplaymakeup
voice_to_text: I do not know if I have it in me to attend big name anime conventions anymore cause the last one that I went to which was MCM London last weekend was so overwhelming and it made me feel so incredibly unsafe and I kind of feel like people have forgotten how to behave when it comes to each other when it comes to creators and when it comes to anime conventions I wanna quickly preface that I do genuinely enjoy getting to meet you guys I love interacting with you I love seeing your cosplays and I love hearing what you have to say however I didn't expect it to get to a point where I am treated more like a show pony than a person at a space that I used to feel comfortable it got so bad at the anime convention I was attending last weekend that I ended up sitting on the floor with my food I put my noise cancelling headphones on and I had two friends around me and I was sitting there in tears and I still had people coming over to me asking for a photo and the thing is I totally understand that for a lot of people this is their opportunity to come and say hello they may have been looking for you around the convention they may have been really excited for this or they feel that that's the only opportunity say hello very general piece of con-etiquette is that if somebody is sitting down and eating or somebody is sitting down on the sidelines you leave them alone I was also stalked for the first day and a half of the convention to the point where I had to hide in the back and basically ask my friends to help me out the intent was almost certainly not malicious but the outcome was still the same I was made to feel incredibly uncomfortable I also feel like I shouldn't have to say this but following around a creator or a cosplayer or just anyone at an anime convention is also not appropriate now again I understand that for a lot of people this can be a space to make new friends but just because you recognize a cosplayer or a creator that you like or admire does not mean that you're automatically entitled to build a friendship or relationship with them at that moment or to follow them around in the hopes that they will give you attention I had people push in front of my friends and directly insert themselves between me and my friends when we were having a conversation and hanging out together in order to talk to me I had people pulling on my clothes and my backpack I had people kind of grabbing me from behind to get my attention and it's annoying because I genuinely really treasure the opportunity to be able to meet you guys and being able to be in a space I really really enjoy with everybody else but it really got to a point where it was just not safe anymore where I couldn't move without being stopped where I couldn't go to the bathroom without somebody pointing out who I was making it a big deal and this wasn't like every couple of minutes this was every couple of steps I always wanna give people the time for taking photos or interactions but I simply cannot pour from an empty cup my presence at these events doesn't automatically entitle you to touch me to grab me to follow me around again I feel really bad saying it because I feel like I'm a bad person for having to set these boundaries but I cannot tell you how uncomfortable and unhappy I was when I left that space content creators and cosplayers that you admire are people too

voice_to_text: I've never understood why so many people think Light Yagami was a smart character. We're watching the story from his perspective, and we constantly hear his internal monologue as he talks about how he is the most brilliant person to have ever lived, how no one can hold up to his rigorous intellectual might. voice_to_text: If Mushoku Tensei isn't supposed to be a redemption story, then what's the point in making Rudius so awful? You know, the kind of guy who constantly harasses women, and when two girls are bullying a friend of his, his solution to the bullying is to kidnap them and tie them up in his bedroom. If you're going to give a character flaws that glaring, or indeed any personality traits, they need to serve a purpose in the narrative. That's why I had assumed that Mushoku Tensei was supposed to be a redemption story. You know, a tale of someone overcoming those flaws and then atoning for the damage they caused. Because if it isn't, then what is it? Because I'll tell you what Mushoku Tensei is not. It's not a tragedy, the kind of story where the heroes own serious flaws end up leading to his destruction. Or even a comedy like South Park or it's Always Sunny in Philadelphia, where you're supposed to laugh at the protagonist for being a terrible person. No, Mushoku Tensei maintains the tone of a fantasy adventure. It's just one where the protagonist touches children. And if that's not meant to be a crime that he needs to face justice for, then either this story sees that only as a flaw on the same level as being unemployed, or it's just included as pandering to the edgy kids who enjoy subversive content for its own sake.

Something that seems to confuse a lot of people is the idea that dodging a light speed attack does not make you light speed. Let me break down why that is with this diagram right here. Let's say you got Person A and Person B. Person B decides to fire a laser beam at Person A. Person A responds by moving their head out of the way, allowing the laser beam to just pass right by them. This laser beam is moving at light speed. However, that person's head was not moving at light speed. Hopefully this makes it, like, easier to understand. But let's say that the laser beam leaves the person's hand and travels 10 feet to get to their opponent, and the person that moved their head out of the side moved their head 6 inches. It took the same amount of time for this laser beam to move 10 feet as it did for this person's head to move 6 inches. Since this covered less distance in the same amount of time, this movement is not relative, speed wise, to the movement of that laser beam. Now, this is also assuming that they started moving their head when the laser was fired, but that's not really how our brains work. Good analogue for this is pitchers and batters in baseball. On average, it takes less than half a second for a fastball to leave the pitcher's hand and make it to home plate. And yet the Average reaction time in the MLB is point seven, five or three quarters of a second. The way that they're still able to hit these fastballs even though their reaction time isn't fast enough to do so is by predicting where the ball is going to go and starting to swing the bat before the pitcher even throws the ball. In the context of a fight, this would be someone looking at the opponent's weapon and determining where it's aiming and preemptively moving out of the path of that projectile. How would you take a situation like this and make it a light speed feat? Well, let's take the same situation. You have two people 10 feet apart. One of them is charging up a laser beam. Person A is being attacked. Person B is charging laser beam. So Person B fires their laser. Now, in this situation, in the time that it takes that laser to travel the 10 feet to the target, that target is able to move 10 feet out of the way. Because they moved 10 feet in the same amount of time that it took that laser beam to travel 10 feet. That would make this feet light speed, because the person is actually moving at the same speed as that laser beam.

voice_to_text: I hate to say you guys, but it might not be Gojo now. I had this thought after the hype had died down from the stream, but there were multiple reasons to why this could not be Gojo. And for the record, I hope it is, but I have to be unbiased here. For one, because of where the students are currently, it wouldn't make much sense. One of the entire premises of Gojo coming back prior was the fact that the students weren't going to defeat Sukina, so Gojo would need to come back for someone to stand a chance. With Yuji not only landing another Black Flash directly to Sukina's heart, but with Todo being around and discombobulating him with Boogie woogie, things are looking really good for the heroes right now, so it seems like really weird timing that the heroes are winning and that's when Gojo comes back. Reason 2 it was purposely ambiguous. If Akutami wanted us to know that Gojo would come back, I don't feel like he would be as ambiguous as he was. Ending it on a cliffhanger allows Akutami the option to not have Gojo come back and this actually be a fake up for something else. And as we know right? When someone's about to lose, they have visions all of the time. And Gojo was the strongest opponent Sukan ever faced. I can see people arguing the fact that they weren't in a good spot because Sukan was About to open up his domain expansion. But remember, they can't resist his domain for a small time because both Toto and Yuji have a simple domain. Not only that, but if the Fire Arrow were to come out again, because Toto can swap things so fast with his new instrument, he could easily swap Yuji and Toto out with the crows again to keep them safe from Tsukana's domain expansion, basically making it Nolan void. So again, in a lot of ways, Yuji and the heroes are in a good spot right now. And again I state I want Gojo to come back, but one, I have to always stay unbiased, and two, there's a lot of evidence pointing to the fact that it could not be Gojo. video_description: Xdefiant has the makings to be a top 3 FPS game and compete for call of duty’s player base 👀 #gaming #gamer #games #xdefiant #cod #esportscenter
voice_to_text: X defiant is about to be a top three FPS game, all thanks to a major decision that players have been begging to see from call of duty. The peak call of duty games and X defiant actually have a lot of things in common, one of them being the brains behind the operation, Mark Rubin, who worked for Activision as the executive producer during the Modern Warfare series. But more importantly, he understands better than anyone that skill based matchmaking has played a huge factor in a call of duty struggles. So today the team released a statement confirming there will be no skill based matchmaking in the casual playlist for X Defiance. The statement continues on saying skill based matchmaking means every casual game is repetitive, constantly repeating matches that are just as stressful as ranked. We believe casual playlist should be fun and varied, similar to how prime call of duty was. X defiant will find matches in order of these priorities latency avoided, players, party size, region, input device, and then platform. Once in the lobby. Teams will still be balanced though. They also confirmed that ranked will be added in a future season, and those matches will be prioritized based on ranked points.

I don't think people understand how big of a role animation plays in deciding how good an anime series is. Always see people saying stuff like oh, animation can't carry animes. It does. It very much does. Whether you like to believe it or not, animation is a huge reason as to why people start watching a series. A big reason why anime such as Demon Slayer and Jujutsu Kaisen are so popular is because of their insane animation production. Now, I'm not trying to say that the only reason why they're popular is because of their animation, but you cannot deny that good animation plays a big role in boosting a series of popularity. For example, Boruto had one episode where they had phenomenal animation, and this episode was enough to spark back a wave of popularity into the Boruto series. Imagine how popular a series like Boruto or even My Hero Academia would be if they had the same level of animation as another series like Demon Slayer or Jujutsu Kaisen. So many more people would be watching these series if they had insane animation. So yeah, people really can't deny how big of a role animation plays in anime.

I'm confused. How is Code Geass a shojo? Now I understand the confusion because people use shonen, shojo, josei, and seinen to describe genres when they are just demographics. Basically, who is the target audience? Shonen just means that the target audience is adolescent boys. So basically young teenagers to young adults. Show Joe is the same thing, but for adolescent girls, and then say Nen is targeted towards adult men and Joe, Say, is targeted towards adult women. Typically, the easiest way to figure out what the target demographic is to a manga series is to just look at the magazine that it's released in. For example, anything released in Shonen Jump is clearly a shonen. However, Code Geassa Lucia the rebellion was released in Osaka Magazine, which is a Shojo magazine. The target audience for everything in this magazine is adolescent girls. But if you think of, like, the demographic and the genre as the same thing, it's gonna get really confusing, if I asked you to point out which one of these three is the seinen, I bet your first guess wouldn't be Apothecary Diaries. In case you're wondering, this series right here is called Queen's Quality, and this one is called Requiem of the Rose King. Those two are both Shojo, and they both fall into the genre of dark fantasy.

voice_to_text: the internet is debating right now whether new television shows should drop all of their episodes at once or do it weekly I've read all the comments it's like 50 50 and even I don't know what the right answer is here because there's a lot of things that need to be consider I just wanna say the reason why this is happening right now is really cool it's very rare that we get two very good shows happening at the same time with fallout and X men 97 fallout dropped all these episodes at once this past week in the Amazon Prime and X Men 97 is still going on Disney I wanna talk about why both release strategies can be positive first for dropping them all at once you don't have to pay for a streaming service longer than one month I think this allows for a property that is new to a lot of people to hook them better if you have all the episodes at one time rather than releasing it week to week because I feel like they could fall out of interest with it third not releasing it all at once can really hinder the flow of a show we saw this very recently with invincible season 2 now why weekly is good you get to talk about characters that you love with your friends for months and months what could be better than that seasons of television shows don't come out as often as they used to so when you expand one it narrows this gap just the little bit lastly if every single episode of a show is good then a week to week basis feels warranted I feel like people are missing one important thing when it comes to this debate Netflix introduced streaming like online streaming in January of 2007 so that means that we have had the ability to binge now for 14 years there are adults in the world right now who have never had to wait week to week for a show so I wouldn't be surprised at all if they get a little bit frustrated that they don't get their content all at once even after all this information I still don't know what my decision will be I think it depends on the show but I don't know let me know in the comments what you think

To a child who isn't loved properly, the answer one might expect is that they start to hate the person who doesn't give them the love they need. But far from it, the reality is that the child becomes filled with shame, a sense that it's profoundly unworthy, dirty, soiled, sinful, ugly, embarrassing. The child is unable to redirect the blame outwards. It doesn't ask what's wrong with my parents for not loving me adequately? It simply wonders in a fullon way what have I done wrong in order to have ended up on the receiving end of my parents disapproval? The child prefers to attack itself for being bad than to confront a yet more awful possibility that it's entirely dependent for its well being on inadequate and unkind parental figures. The child searches for explanations for the lack of love it has to endure and comes up with all the wrong answers. It concludes I've not been impressive enough, and therefore it undertakes enormous efforts to prove to itself and outsiders that it does nevertheless deserve to exist. At school, this kind of child might try seven times as hard as any other to show that it's clever and good. Or else a child may go down an anti social route and graffiti the nearby underpass as a desperate way of giving out would form to a feeling of badness it's tortured by inside. There is so sadly no way out from the burden of shame available either By trying to be extremely good or extremely bad, the only solution is to work against the grain of forgetting, in order to perceive for the first time an awful possibility that one could never perceive as a child, that one has done nothing wrong at all, that wrong was done to one

voice_to_text: What was your luckiest manga find? Mine is really random, but it takes place two and a half years ago, November 2021. I was in Barcelona, Spain. This was a time when manga collecting was really difficult. Big manga like one piece, Naruto, bleach, etc. Were really, really hard to find. And I was really, really close to finishing my one piece collection. So one of the days I was there, I walked into a small comic shop in a random spot in Barcelona and found two volumes of one piece that I was missing at the time. Those volumes being 13 and 23. These, if you don't know, and if you didn't collect back then, were impossible to find. I literally could not find them anywhere in the US at all. Me and the store owner even had a conversation about it when I was buying the volumes, and I was telling him about how hard it is to find manga in the US at the time, and he was really surprised, because in Spain have so much manga. They're constantly printing manga, they're constantly releasing new manga. So for him it was like, really? You really had to find them here? But hey, I was happy to have them. And I think I finished my collection like three months later, which was amazing.

Naruto community as a whole, can we like, collectively do each other a favor and stop giving Naruto credit for things it didn't do as well? Naruto is one of the best any manga series ever made. Can we please stop acting like Naruto inspired literally everything that came after it? Because it didn't. Before I even get into the fact that this guy just blatantly lied, I'm gonna point something else out. One who unironically says that Asta is a wannabe. Naruto not only knows nothing about Asta, but they know nothing about Naruto. Every single time I've seen someone try to say that Asta's a Naruto clone, they are always reaching. Oh, and back to the fact that this guy was lying. Yeah, I saw your other comments said the creator of Black Clover said Naruto heavily inspired it. Yeah, no he didn't. Two actual confirmed inspirations for Black Clover are bleach and Yuyu Hakusho. And anyone who has seen either one of those two and Black Clover can tell you that it's inspired by it. What's even funnier is that anytime somebody brings up that Black Clover copies Naruto, the reasons are always bad. The main ones that people try to bring up is that oh, well, you know, Asta has an inner demon and Naruto has Kurama. And Asta wants to be the wizard king and Naruto wanted to be the hokage. As if Naruto started either one of those tropes to be that guy. But Like, Naruto did not start wanting to be number one at something, nor did he start the inner demon trope. Y'all can't give Naruto credit for everything. We're gonna ignore the fact that Goku wants to be the strongest? Or ignore that Luffy wants to be the Pirate King now? Naruto wanting to be the hokage was the first thing to ever happen, right? So funny that people try to draw comparisons between Asta and Liebe and Naruto and Kurama. Because again, Naruto was not an inspiration for Black Clover. Bleach was. So why people are comparing Naruto and Kurama when Ichigo and zangitsu were actually the inspiration is beyond me. Don't even get me started on the people who try to say that you know and know well. Or like Sasuke and Sakura. Stop. People can sit there and call me a Naruto hater, but I'm like the people that are whining about that. I was the one who was actually watching it all. It was airing on tsunami, so I don't really care how they feel about it. Moral of the story if you think that Asta or Black Clover copied Naruto, you're wrong. Believe it.

flashbacks are dangerous they're one of the more dangerous  things you can write if you don't handle them right they can derail your book some of you might have seen  my video on  three things to cut from your novel and think oh man that guy hates flashbacks I actually don't not as a writer and not as a reader my concern is that  a lot of writers mess up on flashbacks so here are three things to watch out for 1. priority  ask yourself whether the content  of your flashback is way more interesting  than your present moment story you wanna make sure that  your present moment story is  hefty enough to handle a flashback  without it being overwhelmed  2. length writers have incredible imaginations which means sometimes they write  backstories that are far too long take a hard look at your length and make sure you haven't written too much backstory  3 placement it’s usually dangerous to give  a lot of backstory  at the beginning of your book by the middle of your book you have a lot more latitude
